05409nam a22007815i 9780674062979DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20112011mau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)840441203  a97806740629797 a10.4159/harvard.97806740629792doi  a(DE-B1597)178293  a(OCoLC)768411326  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aQB36.G2bP48 2011eb 7aSCI0340002bisacsh04a709.02/4223  aSG 5552rvk0(DE-625)rvk/143062:1 aPeterson, Mark A., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aGalileo's Muse :bRenaissance Mathematics and the Arts /cMark A. Peterson. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2011] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (352 p.) :b22 line illustrations; 2 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPrologue -- t1. Galileo, Humanist -- t2. The Classical Legacy -- tPoetry -- t3. The Plan of Heaven -- t4. The Vision of God -- tPainting -- t5. The Power of the Lines -- t6. The Skin of the Lion -- tMusic -- t7. The Orphic Mystery -- t8. Kepler and the Music of the Spheres -- tArchitecture -- t9. Figure and Form -- t10 The Dimensions of Hell -- t11. Mathematics Old and New -- t12. Transforming Mathematics -- t13. The Oration -- tEpilogue -- tNotes -- tAcknowledgments -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMark Peterson makes an extraordinary claim in this fascinating book focused around the life and thought of Galileo: it was the mathematics of Renaissance arts, not Renaissance sciences, that became modern science. Galileo's Muse argues that painters, poets, musicians, and architects brought about a scientific revolution that eluded the philosopher-scientists of the day, steeped as they were in a medieval cosmos and its underlying philosophy.According to Peterson, the recovery of classical science owes much to the Renaissance artists who first turned to Greek sources for inspiration and instruction. Chapters devoted to their insights into mathematics, ranging from perspective in painting to tuning in music, are interspersed with chapters about Galileo's own life and work. Himself an artist turned scientist and an avid student of Hellenistic culture, Galileo pulled together the many threads of his artistic and classical education in designing unprecedented experiments to unlock the secrets of nature.In the last chapter, Peterson draws our attention to the Oratio de Mathematicae laudibus of 1627, delivered by one of Galileo's students. This document, Peterson argues, was penned in part by Galileo himself, as an expression of his understanding of the universality of mathematics in art and nature. It is ";entirely Galilean in so many details that even if it is derivative, it must represent his thought,"; Peterson writes. An intellectual adventure, Galileo’s Muse offers surprising ideas that will capture the imagination of anyone—scientist, mathematician, history buff, lover of literature, or artist—who cares about the humanistic roots of modern science.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 7aSCIENCE / History.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE-BOOK GESAMTPAKET / COMPLETE PACKAGE 2011z9783110261189oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE-BOOK PACKAGE ENGLISH LANGUAGES TITLES 2011z978311026123308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE-BOOK PAKET SCIENCE TECHNOLOGY AND MEDICINE 2011z9783110261202oZDB-23-DMN08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013 (Canada)z978311075606708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044220540uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/harvard.978067406297940uhttps: